text: The movie looks great since they have designed alot more detail into some of the peculiarities and contraptions than is in the book but the story being told is very different from the book by the looks of it.  I am reading the book at the moment.  Emma's peculiarity is Fire, not air, and the ship wreck, Emma and Jacob went to talk on was only just below the surface so that they could stand on it out on the water.  They never dove down to it and Emma certainly didn't fill it with air.  It looks like how Jacob comes across the Home is quite different (Emma never invited him to come and see the rest as the trailer seems to suggest she does).  Since Emma is now the one that floats, the much younger girl in the book that floats (Olive) doesn't seem to be there any more.  The girl who could make plants grow was much older in the book than the one portrayed doing so in the trailer and is described as being wild in appearance, as is the photo of her shown in the book.  Still it might be just one of those movies where you have to ignore the book and just enjoy the movie in its own right.  So long as it is a story told well it looks great!!

text: Just a few things to know if you have no read the books: 1. It is not like the X-Men, this is largely due to the fact that their abilities are secret from the normal world so there is no "fitting in", they live exclusively in time loops 2. It's been said before but Emma and Olive's peculiarities are switched. 3. Of course the movie can't be perfect but taking away Emma's peculiarity really takes away a whole dimension of her character. Reading the book you can tell how many of their peculiarities affect their personalities and their stories as people 4. The twins in the masks are not in the story, a photograph of them is seen but they are not actually on the island 5. Claire, Jake and Miss Peregrine seem to be the most accurate so far

text: I will never understand why YouTube thinks we need to see a 3 second preview of the trailer.... in the video that is the trailer. as if to say "hey, you searched for the video... well here's a brief look at the video you literally are going to watch. it doesn't matter that this is technically you're getting the video, here's a sneak peek of it". I mean what a waste what redundant.... I don't know what's worse this or the thing that I unaffectionatly refer to a "trailer of a trailer". you know, the videos that claim to be a movie teaser trailer but instead it is a shorter version of the official trailer that gives the full length trailer's release date, and tells you to watch it. it's usually only a week away from the actual trailer if that. in other words instead of releasing a trailer to get us hyped for a movie they're showing us a snippet of a trailer to advertise that trailer which is advertising the movie. while I have always felt that a good trailer is a perfect marriage between marketing and art it is still technically an advertisement and let's be real... a trailer for a trailer is essentially advertising a commercial. what sense does that make. and usually the actual trailer was only a week away so why bother wasting the film editors time to make this thing when a finished trailer could be released in a matter of days. actually if I recall correctly, the trailer to pixels trailer was released on the very same day.... as Pixels trailer! what?! I came to watch a trailer guys. why arbitrarily extend the video length by adding a few seconds of footage from a video at the very beginning of the video you are uploading. it's probably just that, to extend the video length just a little so that they can make a few extra pennies. who cares if we already have a completed video with a beginning middle and end edited by talented people who know how to show what clips and when, insuring a well-paced and balanced film that will advertise a movie as well as provide a mild emotional experience for viewers, let's make it a few seconds longer because that will add up more cash.... nobody will notice.  yeah I know it's just nitpicking but hey it annoys me

text: At first I was excited to hear that this story was being made into a movie, but with all of the changes that have been made, I can't bring myself to see it.  My main complaint is that the major character changes (switching of peculiarities between characters, mainly) completely alter the story and key plot points.  And don't get me started on casting choices!  I am a fairly open minded person when it comes to casting, but there comes a point when certain people should not be playing certain characters.  For those who haven't read the book, I'm sure that this movie will be wonderful.  For fans of the book, you should find something else on which to spend your time and money.

text: Nope. Done.  Don't take the title of a book for a movie unless you intend to follow closely to it.  This isn't the 'Miss Peregrine's home for peculiar children' story I know.  It's like if they made the 'Harry Potter' series with Ron as the boy who lived and having Harry come to Hogwarts his first year popular and living with Hagrid instead of Vernon.  Like I'd still go to see it but I wouldn't call it Harry Potter.  I know Ransom Riggs was there as they made it, so I am clinging to the hope that they listened to him along the way and trusting his creativity to help the producers make a beautiful movie from his book, I just would have liked if they had chosen a different title and had it say <insert movie title> based on the series MPHPC by RR.  Either way, it looks like an interesting movie, but I think they will kill it by false advertising.  That is all

text: All those "They changed too much stuff, it gonna sucks!" comments... Wait 'till you see it, and consider it a separate universe. That's what you should do with any movie inspired of books. Dreamworks and Disney take inspiration in books and stories very often, and almost no one complain even if it's very different that the source material. Harry Potter, Lord of the Ring and Hunger Games movies still ended up pretty popular... See where I'm going? Being both an avid reader and movie fan, by simply considering movies and books as different universes of a multiverse, I've almost always enjoyed the movies as much as the books. I can't wait for that movie, and since I've yet to read that book series, I definitely gonna read it either before or after watching the movie.

text: Pros and Cons of the movie: (Spoiler Alert!)  Cons: 1. Switching the powers of Emma and Olive. I don't think that was necessary. 2. Butterfield's acting is average. 3. It isn't as dark as compared to the book. (Well, maybe, the scenes had to be softened to embrace a great number of audience.) 4. The script is average. Which probably explained number 2. 5. Some scenes that are meant to be funny didn't make me laugh. 6. I thought wights don't have peculiar powers. 7. What did they do to Miss Avocet?! 8. Is it as good as the book? No. Is it better than the book? Definitely not. 9. Am I disappointed? Yes. Because it's Tim Burton. I was expecting more. He, Guillermo Del Toro and the late and the great Alfred Hitchcock are my heroes to this kind of films. However, this movie looks rushed and scattered. I could see from one transition to another several scenes were cut, and it isn't a clean cut. It looks like Zack Snyder did this.  Pros: 1. Every peculiar child is given a chance to fight using their peculiarity; compared to the first book, they were just running and ALMOST all the fighting depended on Jake. Like what Emma said to Jake in the last act of the movie, "You taught us how to be brave." 2. Emma's shoes! They are so cool!  3. Olive ‚ù§Ô∏è Enoch. I think they look good together. Let's just give them a chance. 4. This is my favorite scene--Jake meeting Abe in a different loop, wherein it is implied that Abe was able to give Jake pointers about peculiardom. I was expecting Ransom would include this in one of the Peculiar Children trilogy; however, Abe's role just ended after his death, leaving Jake seeking answers on his own. 5. The children working as a team. Somehow I felt a vibe of Harry Potter and Narnia, especially when they departed January 2016 timeloop via ship. Which is a good thing. 6. The twins are serpents after all. I like their petrifying ability. 7. Am I expecting a sequel? Yes.  My rating: 6/10

text: Ok, ok, ok. A friend of ours is moving a whole state away and she wanted to hang out one last time tonight.   (Wall of random thoughts incoming, as it's 12:34 at night.)   I went into this movie with no expections. I had seen no trailers. I went in completely blind, expecting Nanny McPhee with minorly superpowered kids. A cute fluffy film.  HOO BOY, WHERE TO BEGIN?  I didn't expect to enjoy this movie. The characters were charming, Miss Peregrine is just awesome, and the villains are hammy, yet appealing.  (The setting was just relatable to me, too. I'm biased, sue me.)  Didn't expect to see Samuel L. Jackson, because apparently I live under a rock. Good God he was hilarious. Watch the air scene, you'll see what I'm talking about. You can tell he's having the time of his life hamming it up and not giving a care.  The fantasy elements are great, and this is Tim Burton's best in awhile. (Heh, one look at an uninviting suburb full of offputting people with false smiles, and you know it's a Burton movie. There was even a shot where a bunch of relatives got all up in Jake's face acting waaaaay too happy to see him. It reminded me of Edward Scissorhands.)  The editing is a little jarring sometimes, but it's not distracting.  The main character is a little bland... but that's the point. He's ordinary, and that doesn't make the kid any less likable.   I DID NOT. EXPECT. EYE GORE. AND. SLENDERMEN. GIANT SLENDERMEN wearing carnations. I was so giddy and uncomfortable, and my friends were all cracking up.  Truly the best Slenderman movie that isn't even a Slenderman movie  I also loved the battle scene with the reanimated skeletons. Pirate skelebros vs Giant Slendermen. So cool.  So, yeah, a pretty fun movie. Not oscar material, but it piques my interest enough to go check out the books. Thumbs up.

text: Am I the only one who liked the movie? The book series is no doubt amazing, but I really enjoyed the surprise and uniqueness of the movie from the book. It's definitely heard of where protagonists have romance interests with girls involved with fire, but there's never been a boy who pulls his lover through the air by rope. I also loved the imagery and the characters of the movie, too, despite some being different than the book (take Bronwyn, Emma, and Olive for example), and I love the fact that Tim Burton used the Twins in the series as well since they really showed off eye-candy to the movie's appeal.   Yes, this film is almost completely different than the book, but it doesn't ruin the story. All that Tim Burton did was take the original story and world of Miss Peregrine's Home for Peculiar Children and shape it into his own imagination. Take note that this movie didn't necessarily have to be a copy of the book, it was simply based off the book.   I was quite pleased and surprised with this film.
